n to Pro Tools with the ability to change BPM, rhythm, and feel. Do I hear a GarageBand, Acid, or Recycle from the choir?  To slice, dice, and conform existing audio regions, loops, or tracks, follow  these steps: 1. 2.  Make sure your tracks are tick based. Make your selection based on the exact number of bars you want to work with in the region s  or track s . It has to be an even number of bars and consistent meter to work. This is the most important part of the entire process. If you don’t get your selection right, you are doomed from the get-go.  See the selection tech- niques in “Creating the Vital Loop” earlier in this chapter.  If your selection is a loop, then you can double-click with the Selector tool to select the entire region or single-click with the Grabber tool. Bring up Beat Detective by typing F+Keypad+8   Ctrl+Keypad+8  see Figure 3.40 .  Figure 3.40 Beat Detective in Pro Tools 7  Select the Region Separation radio button on the left side of the Beat Detective window. The first two buttons are for generating bars and beats markers and for extracting grooves from selections. Click Capture Selection if you know the BPM of the loop; this should automati- cally enter in the start and end points for your selection. If you don’t know the tempo but the tempo is consistent, use Identify Beat  F+I   Ctrl+I  with the Tempo Ruler enabled to figure the BPM. Identify Beat is a valuable tool in Pro Tools even though most loops identify their BPM. Click the Analyze button to have Beat Detective figure out where the transients are in your track. This starts the slicing process, and in a combination of the next three steps, you will get the slices you desire. Choose your resolution in bars, beats or sub-beats. This will tell Beat Detective how finely to slice up the regions made by analyzing.  3.  4.  5.  6.  7.  131       P R O     T O O L S    O N     A C  I  D  :    T R  I P P I  N G     W  I  T H     B E A T     D E T E C T  I  V E   8.  9.  In the Contains bo