ts in iTunes 4.9 and above and by drawing from its enormous iPod branding as part of the de facto name. This technology may go the way of the 8-track, but it may also  220    S L O O T     O R P     F O     E D  I S T U O     E F I L     R O    ,  E C N U O B     E H T     R E T F A  :  6  R E T P A H C   1.  2.  3.  be a harbinger of things to come in terms of production and content delivery. Wayne’s World was a podcast hit waiting to happen! So what does it take to create and produce a podcast? Depending on the how deep you want go, a computer, some music software and hardware, a camera, an Internet connection, and an idea will get you going. Any- one can be a podstar, so lights camera, action! For an audio podcast, follow these steps: Create your show. Okay, that’s like saying move that piano over here. It’s easier said than done, but for argument’s sake, let’s say you just made the best show since Fernwood Tonight. If you are making an audio show, then it’s a little easier technically. You can use most any current audio software to create an audio-only podcast. Video is a bit more complicated, but with the right gear and a little skill, you don’t need to be NBC. This is like the first days of radio and TV. In Pro Tools, bounce your files out as either a WAV  .wav  or AIFF  .aif . This is one of the times to actually use a maximizing plug-in on your master fader. You need to get your track loud and compressed considering that most people will listen back to your cast on less-than-stellar gear.  See “Mastering Your Tracks in Pro Tools” later in this chapter.  In the iTunes preferences, set your import method to whatever format you want to use  Preferences > Advanced > Importing > Import Using . Even with the large bandwidth available these days, you need to compress your files to podcast them. The question is, how much? To compress your files, choose either the AAC or MP3 format. Either format will work well for podcasting. Reports vary on what has the best qualit